<PageLayout
  title="Afamelanotide (Scenesse): the approved drug that treats light by building a tan"
  kicker="Approved drug"
  description="Afamelanotide is the first FDA-approved treatment for erythropoietic protoporphyria — a superpotent α-MSH copy that switches on MC1R to build protective pigment independent of sunlight. It's also the regulated medicine the Melanotan lineage actually produced."
  updated="2026"
  about={[
    { name: 'Afamelanotide', type: 'Drug', sameAs: ['https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Afamelanotide'] },
    { name: 'Melanocortin 1 receptor', type: 'MedicalEntity', sameAs: ['https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Melanocortin_1_receptor'] },
    { name: 'Erythropoietic protoporphyria', type: 'MedicalCondition', sameAs: ['https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Erythropoietic_protoporphyria'] },
  ]}
>
  <KeyTakeaways
    items={[
      'Afamelanotide (brand name Scenesse) is a synthetic, longer-lasting analogue of α-MSH and a selective MC1R agonist — a durable copy of the body’s natural pigment signal.',
      'It was FDA-approved on 8 October 2019, the first treatment ever for erythropoietic protoporphyria (EPP), to increase pain-free light exposure in affected adults.',
      'Its trick is to drive protective eumelanin independent of sunlight, so patients build up pigment in advance rather than relying on the light that hurts them.',
      'It is delivered as a 16 mg controlled-release implant placed under the skin by a clinician about every two months — not a pill or self-injection.',
      'It is the approved, regulated medicine of the “Melanotan-I” lineage — the legitimate counterpart to the unapproved tanning peptide Melanotan II.',
    ]}
  />

  <p>
    Afamelanotide — sold as <strong>Scenesse</strong> — is the clearest therapeutic use
    of the melanocortin pigment system: a drug that treats a light-sensitivity disease
    by building a protective tan on purpose. It is a synthetic, sturdier copy of
    <a href="/alpha-msh">α-MSH</a>, and it works by doing deliberately what sunlight
    normally does by accident — switching on <a href="/receptors/mc1r">MC1R</a> to make
    dark, shielding pigment.<Cite n={1} />
  </p>

  <h2>The disease it treats</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>Erythropoietic protoporphyria (EPP)</strong> is a rare inherited disorder in
    which a molecule called protoporphyrin IX builds up in the skin. In sunlight that
    build-up makes the skin burn with intense, disabling pain — so severe that patients
    often structure their whole lives around avoiding light.<Cite n={3} /> Before 2019 there
    was no approved treatment; the only option was avoidance.
  </p>

  <h2>How it works — pigment on demand</h2>
  <p>
    Afamelanotide binds predominantly to MC1R and drives eumelanin production
    <em>independently of sunlight</em>.<Cite n={1} /> That independence is the whole point.
    A person with EPP cannot safely build a tan the normal way, because the ultraviolet
    exposure that would do it is exactly what causes them pain. Afamelanotide supplies
    the receptor signal directly, so protective pigment accumulates in advance — lengthening
    the time patients can tolerate light before symptoms start.<Cite n={1} />
  </p>
  <p>
    The FDA approved it on <strong>8 October 2019</strong> to increase pain-free light
    exposure in adults with a history of phototoxic reactions from EPP — the first therapy
    ever cleared for the condition, granted under Priority Review and Orphan Drug
    designation.<Cite n={2} />
  </p>

  <h2>An unusual delivery system</h2>
  <p>
    Afamelanotide is as distinctive in form as in mechanism. Rather than a pill or a
    self-injection, it is a <strong>16 mg controlled-release implant</strong> — roughly the
    size of a grain of rice — inserted under the skin by a trained clinician about every
    two months.<Cite n={1} /> The implant releases the drug slowly, keeping the protective
    pigment topped up between visits. That design suits a preventive, always-on job:
    maintaining a baseline of photoprotection rather than reacting dose by dose.
  </p>

  <h2>The Melanotan connection</h2>
  <p>
    Afamelanotide is also the answer to a common confusion. It began life as
    <strong>"Melanotan-I,"</strong> one of the α-MSH analogues that came out of early
    melanocortin research into synthetic tanning agents. Afamelanotide is the branch of
    that work that was carried all the way through trials to approval — the regulated
    medicine the lineage produced. The <a href="/melanotan">grey-market tanning peptide
    Melanotan II</a> is the other, unapproved branch. They are relatives, not the same
    product, and the difference between them is exactly the difference between a tested,
    approved drug and an unregulated one. See <a href="/pt-141-vs-melanotan">PT-141 vs
    Melanotan</a> for how tangled this family tree gets.
  </p>

  <h2>The honest bottom line</h2>
  <p>
    Afamelanotide is a small, elegant proof that the melanocortin pigment switch is
    genuinely druggable and genuinely useful. It does not cure EPP — it manages it, by
    turning a cosmetic side effect of melanocortin agonists, skin darkening, into the
    therapeutic goal. For the receptor it acts on, see
    <a href="/receptors/mc1r">MC1R — the pigment switch</a>; for the oral drug chasing the
    same target, see <a href="/dersimelagon">dersimelagon</a>.
  </p>

